39
00:02:24,030 --> 00:02:26,530
And to calculate an odds ratio, it's very
simple.

40
00:02:26,530 --> 00:02:29,650
So, if you're looking at some kind of
exposure and you want to know,

41
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:32,820
what's the odds of getting the outcome in
the exposed group?

42
00:02:32,820 --> 00:02:34,680
You just look at cells a and b.

43
00:02:34,680 --> 00:02:37,380
So the odds is going to be your chance of
getting it

44
00:02:37,380 --> 00:02:38,790
divided by your chance of not getting it.

45
00:02:38,790 --> 00:02:40,340
So that's a divided by b.

46
00:02:40,340 --> 00:02:44,040
That's the odds of getting the outcome in
the exposed group.

47
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:46,930
The odds of getting the outcome in the
unexposed group therefore will be

48
00:02:46,930 --> 00:02:48,330
c divided by d.

49
00:02:48,330 --> 00:02:51,360
So it's an odds ratio, so we divide those
two odds.

50
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:54,410
Mathematically however it's even simpler
to calculate than this.

51
00:02:54,410 --> 00:02:57,420
Because if you multiply by the reciprocal
here you realize that

52
00:02:57,420 --> 00:03:00,700
to calculate the odds ratio, from a two by
two table, all you have to do,

53
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:05,270
is do a times d, divided by b times c, so
just use those cross products.

54
00:03:05,270 --> 00:03:06,560
Very straight forward to calculate.

55
00:03:08,660 --> 00:03:12,640
Now, I'll just note, that if you're doing
