00:11:58,330 --> 00:12:01,390
And what's really interesting here is
notice that the standard error

226
00:12:01,390 --> 00:12:05,070
is related to the reciprocal of those cell
sizes.

227
00:12:05,070 --> 00:12:06,490
So what does that actually mean?

228
00:12:06,490 --> 00:12:08,060
Well, just let's plug in some numbers.

229
00:12:09,110 --> 00:12:13,440
What if we had a study where we ended up
with a very small cell a, you know,

230
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:17,470
had a 1 in it, and maybe cell b has ten,
and cell c is 100, and cell d has 1000.

231
00:12:17,470 --> 00:12:21,370
What's that going to mean in terms of the
standard error?

232
00:12:21,370 --> 00:12:26,826
If we plug into the standard error
formula, we notice is we get 1 over 1,

233
00:12:26,826 --> 00:12:31,730
plus one over 10, plus 1 over 100, plus 1
over 1000.

234
00:12:31,730 --> 00:12:35,585
Now, notice what that breaks down to
inside the square root.

235
00:12:35,585 --> 00:12:40,380
Though cell a contributes a one to the
variability.

236
00:12:40,380 --> 00:12:42,620
All the other cells contribute decimal
places.

237
00:12:42,620 --> 00:12:44,970
So this just ends up being 1.111, right.

238
00:12:44,970 --> 00:12:46,790
So everything else is just a decimal
place.

239
00:12:46,790 --> 00:12:47,720
Cell a,

240
00:12:47,720 --> 00:12:53,490
almost completely, the smallest cell,
almost completely drives the variability.

241
00:12:53,490 --> 00:12:54,890
And that makes a lot of sense.

242
00:12:54,890 --> 00:12:57,720
In terms of how much variability there is
in an odds ratio,

243
00:12:57,720 --> 00:13:00,530
the smallest cell is really the limiting
factor.

244
00:13:00,530 --> 00:13:04,294
Because imagine that I were, was to change
cell a by just 1%.

245
00:13:04,294 --> 00:13:08,640
Subtract 1 or add 1, that's going to have
a huge impact on the odds ratio.

246
00:13:08,640 --> 00:13:12,030
Whereas if I were to add or subtract 1
from cell b or cell c or

247
00:13:12,030 --> 00:13:15,520
cell d it's not going to have much a an
impact on the odds ratio so,

248
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:18,230
the variability of an odds ratio really is
driven.

249
00:13:18,230 --> 00:13:21,210
By the size of the smallest cell and that
insight is kind of burred in

250
00:13:21,210 --> 00:13:23,565
the standard error there so I think that's
neat.

251
00:13:23,565 --> 00:13:28,130
Alright, so just to summarize the natural
log of the odds

252
00:13:28,130 --> 00:13:32,360
ratio luckily is normally distributed, the
mean value is whatever the true value of

253
00:13:32,360 --> 00:13:36,290
the natural log of the odds ratio ratio is
under the null hypothesis, that's zero.

254
00:13:36,290 --> 00:13:38,990
And the standard error is that formula
that I just gave you.

255
00:13:38,990 --> 00:13:41,580
We're not going to have to calculate too
many of these by hand in this class, but

256
00:13:41,580 --> 00:13:45,460
again I think just understanding the
distribution here gives you some insight.

257
00:13:45,460 --> 00:13:49,190
So, inferences for the odds the ratio, if
I want to do a hypothesis test.

258
00:13:49,190 --> 00:13:52,310
I want to test whether or not the odds
ratio is one,

259
00:13:52,310 --> 00:13:55,730
which is equivalent to the natural log of
the odds ratio being 0,

260
00:13:55,730 --> 00:13:59,420
so that would be my null hypothesis, if
there's no difference between the groups.

261
00:13:59,420 --> 00:14:01,590
I would just do a z test, because we're on
a normal curve.

262
00:14:01,590 --> 00:14:05,180
I compared the natural log of the odds
ratio that I observed with its standard,

263
00:14:05,180 --> 00:14:07,140
with its standard error.

264
00:14:07,140 --> 00:14:08,962
Simple to calculate.

265
00:14:08,962 --> 00:14:14,170
The 95% confidence interval is similarly
going to be based on the standard error.

266
00:14:14,170 --> 00:14:17,820
Notice, though, that we're going to be
calculating the 95% confidence interval

267
00:14:17,820 --> 00:14:22,210
for the natural log of the odds ratio by
adding and subtracting 1.96.

268
00:14:22,210 --> 00:14:23,260
Times the standard error.

269
00:14:23,260 --> 00:14:26,960
That will give me a confidence interval
for the natural log of the odds ratio.

270
00:14:26,960 --> 00:14:28,600
You don't want to report that in your
paper, though,

271
00:14:28,600 --> 00:14:31,650
because odds ratios are hard enough to
understand.

272
00:14:31,650 --> 00:14:34,680
Don't bother with natural logs of odds
ratios, nobody can understand that.

273
00:14:34,680 --> 00:14:38,200
So what we're going to do, of course, at
the end of the day, is take the upper and

274
00:14:38,200 --> 00:14:43,940
lower bounds and exponentiate them to get
back to an actual odds ratio measure.

275
00:14:43,940 --> 00:14:47,790
And that's going to have an interesting
effect, that,

276
00:14:47,790 --> 00:14:52,270
if you've ever noticed odds ratios and 95%
confidence intervals in the literature,

277
00:14:52,270 --> 00:14:55,300
a lot of people would remark, well,
they're not symmetric.

278
00:14:55,300 --> 00:14:56,480
If you look at the confidence interval,

279
00:14:56,480 --> 00:15:01,900
this was the confidence interval from a
previous module for an odds ratio.

280
00:15:01,900 --> 00:15:03,700
Notice that it's not symmetric.

281
00:15:03,700 --> 00:15:05,250
The 0.243 does not fall right in the
middle.

282
00:15:05,250 --> 00:15:09,850
We actually end up with kind of a high
upper bound, and

283
00:15:09,850 --> 00:15:12,800
the point estimate is closer to the left
bound.

284
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:16,710
Well, this is an effect of exponentiating,
of dealing with logs.

285
00:15:16,710 --> 00:15:19,680
So sometimes in the literature,

286
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:23,670
you'll see that the upper bound for an
odds ratio can be really high.

287
00:15:23,670 --> 00:15:24,660
It might be something like 100.

288
00:15:24,660 --> 00:15:27,060
I've seen ones that have 200, 300.

289
00:15:27,060 --> 00:15:28,290
You know, ridiculously high.

290
00:15:28,290 --> 00:15:29,590
Well, that's because when you
exponentiate,

291
00:15:29,590 --> 00:15:32,440
you're putting back in that right hand
tail.

292
00:15:32,440 --> 00:15:34,420
So the 95% confidence interval for

293
00:15:34,420 --> 00:15:37,130
the natural log of the odds ratio is
symmetric, but for

294
00:15:37,130 --> 00:15:39,580
the odds ratio itself, it's going to have
this, kind of, right skew.

295
00:15:41,410 --> 00:15:44,320
So if you've ever wondered why that is,
that, that's the explanation.

296
00:15:46,210 --> 00:15:48,870
So that's inferences for odds ratios.

297
00:15:48,870 --> 00:15:52,370
Now moving on to just this question, how
to interpret odds ratios.

298
00:15:52,370 --> 00:15:56,170
And then you have to again be very
cautious in your interpretation or

299
00:15:56,170 --> 00:15:58,280
funny things can happen.

300
00:15:58,280 --> 00:16:01,230
So, odds ratios give the increase or

301
00:16:01,230 --> 00:16:03,540
decrease in the relative odds of the
outcome.

302
00:16:03,540 --> 00:16:07,730
Of course, if you say that in your paper
people will look at you cross eyed.

303
00:16:07,730 --> 00:16:11,970
There are certain situations where the
odds ratio can actually be interpreted as

304
00:16:11,970 --> 00:16:16,470
a risk ratio and you'll okay, and this is
the case where you'll have rare outcome.

305
00:16:16,470 --> 00:16:19,490
So if your outcome is rare, it turns out
that the odds ratio and

306
00:16:19,490 --> 00:16:21,770
the risk ratio are pretty close to one
another.

307
00:16:21,770 --> 00:16:24,800
In other words, if you say that, if you
interpret your odds ratio as

308
00:16:24,800 --> 00:16:28,660
the increase or decrease in the risk of
the outcome, you won't be very far off.

309
00:16:28,660 --> 00:16:29,938
The general rule of thumb is that as,

310
00:16:29,938 --> 00:16:34,550
as the outcome incurs at less than 10% of,
say, your reference group,

311
00:16:34,550 --> 00:16:38,520
that's rear enough where the, the odds
ratio and risk ratio are kind of similar.

312
00:16:38,520 --> 00:16:39,990
They can be interpreted in, you know,

313
00:16:39,990 --> 00:16:43,400
they can interpret the odds ratio as a
risk ratio.

314
00:16:43,400 --> 00:16:47,690
However, when the outcome is more common
than this, the odds ratio can

315
00:16:47,690 --> 00:16:51,910
distort the effect size quite a lot, and
you have to interpret things cautiously.

316
00:16:51,910 --> 00:16:55,480
So, if you're doing a case control study,
generally case control studies are run on

317
00:16:55,480 --> 00:16:59,170
rare outcomes so you're likely to have a
rare outcome and it's likely okay,

318
00:16:59,170 --> 00:17:02,990
that you interpret that odds ratio as an
increase or decrease in risk.

319
00:17:02,990 --> 00:17:05,820
However, when you're doing cohort study,
cross sectional study,

320
00:17:05,820 --> 00:17:10,140
randomized trial, all of those usually
involve more common outcomes.

321
00:17:10,140 --> 00:17:13,400
So if you apply logistic regression in one
of those cases and

322
00:17:13,400 --> 00:17:17,150
you get all those odds ratios, be very
careful if your outcome is common and

323
00:17:17,150 --> 00:17:20,550
make sure that you don't interpret those
odds ratios incorrectly.

324
00:17:20,550 --> 00:17:24,750
And just to give you some more examples of
exactly how this works.

325
00:17:24,750 --> 00:17:29,630
So imagine I have a situation where I have
a rare outcome.

326
00:17:29,630 --> 00:17:32,740
Okay, so my outcome occurs in, you know,

327
00:17:32,740 --> 00:17:36,090
3% of my exposed group and 1% of my
reference group.

328
00:17:36,090 --> 00:17:37,180
So my risk ratio is three.

329
00:17:37,180 --> 00:17:39,840
There's a three fold increase in risk in
the exposed group.

330
00:17:39,840 --> 00:17:42,050
What would the corresponding odds ratio be
here?

331
00:17:42,050 --> 00:17:45,650
So the odds ratio would be the risk.

332
00:17:45,650 --> 00:17:47,900
The probability of something happening
divided by the probability of

333
00:17:47,900 --> 00:17:48,540
it not happening.

334
00:17:48,540 --> 00:17:50,110
So, 1 minus the risk.

335
00:17:50,110 --> 00:17:55,110
So my odds, 3% divided by 97% is actually
still

336
00:17:55,110 --> 00:17:57,680
pretty close to 3% because 97% is very
close to 1.

337
00:17:57,680 --> 00:18:00,520
So you're essentially dividing by 1, it
doesn't change things much.

338
00:18:00,520 --> 00:18:04,170
Similarly, in this denominator we would
divide 1% by 99%, but

339
00:18:04,170 --> 00:18:11,100
that odds is essentially still 1% because
the 99% and the 97% are essentially 1.

340
00:18:11,100 --> 00:18:12,200
We end up with a,

341
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:15,360
an odds ratio that's just slightly bigger
than the corresponding risk ratio.

342
00:18:15,360 --> 00:18:19,520
If I were to say, hey, that's a threefold
increase in the risk in the exposed group,

343
00:18:19,520 --> 00:18:21,640
I wouldn't be off, I wouldn't be far off,
that would be fine.

344
00:18:22,970 --> 00:18:26,000
But compare that to the situation where we
have a common outcome.

345
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:29,650
So imagine that we have a situation where
my exposed group has

346
00:18:29,650 --> 00:18:34,580
a 60% risk of having the outcome and my
reference group has a 20% risk.

347
00:18:34,580 --> 00:18:36,370
The risk ratio's still three there.

348
00:18:36,370 --> 00:18:39,010
But look what happen to the odds ration
now.

349
00:18:39,010 --> 00:18:42,620
The odds ratio is calculated by doing the
odds of the exposed group.

350
00:18:42,620 --> 00:18:46,480
That's 60% divided by 40% or three out of
two.

351
00:18:46,480 --> 00:18:47,660
Very three to two.

352
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:53,033
Very different than 60%, and the odds for
the unexposed group is 20% divided by 80%.

353
00:18:53,033 --> 00:18:55,540
When I calculate that out, it comes out to
be an odds ratio of six.

354
00:18:55,540 --> 00:18:58,520
So it's quite distorted from the risk
ratio.

355
00:18:58,520 --> 00:19:00,500
You would not want to look at this odds
ratio and

356
00:19:00,500 --> 00:19:03,340
report it in your paper as a sixfold
increase in risk,

357
00:19:03,340 --> 00:19:05,089
because clearly there's only a threefold
increase in risk.

358
00:19:06,180 --> 00:19:09,120
So again, be careful with common outcomes.

359
00:19:09,120 --> 00:19:12,915
And just to illustrate this a little
further, if you had HRP 259 in fall again,

360
00:19:12,915 --> 00:19:14,840
you can breeze through this, because I,

361
00:19:14,840 --> 00:19:19,600
I've made a lot of these points already in
that class, because it's so important.

362
00:19:19,600 --> 00:19:22,740
But if you have a rare outcome, your odds
ratio is also always going to be

363
00:19:22,740 --> 00:19:25,590
slightly bigger than your risk ratio if
you have a harmful.

364
00:19:26,750 --> 00:19:29,870
Something that's harmful a harmful effect
a risk ratio above one that means your

365
00:19:29,870 --> 00:19:33,930
odds ratio is going to be bigger if you
have a protective effect a risk ratio

366
00:19:33,930 --> 00:19:36,118
below one that means your odds ratio is
going to be a little bit smaller.

367
00:19:36,118 --> 00:19:41,325
But if it's a common outcome those
distortions can be much greater.

368
00:19:41,325 --> 00:19:45,680
And there's actually a direct mathematical
relationship between the odds ratio and

369
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:46,810
risk ratio.

370
00:19:46,810 --> 00:19:51,400
So remember, the odds ratio just involves
having the probabilities of

371
00:19:51,400 --> 00:19:52,410
things not happening.

372
00:19:52,410 --> 00:19:56,050
So we get these extra terms, mult, if we
multiply the risk ratio by

373
00:19:56,050 --> 00:19:58,750
these extra probabilities of things not
happening.

374
00:19:58,750 --> 00:19:59,580
That's the odds ratio.

375
00:19:59,580 --> 00:20:03,740
So this is the direct mathematical
relationship between those two quantities.

376
00:20:03,740 --> 00:20:06,850
If you're having rare outcome, clearly 1
minus something that

377
00:20:06,850 --> 00:20:09,150
doesn't occur very often is going to be
close to one.

378
00:20:09,150 --> 00:20:11,090
So, 1 minus 1% and

379
00:20:11,090 --> 00:20:15,210
1 minus 2%, for example, that quantity
again is going to be very close to one.

380
00:20:15,210 --> 00:20:17,650
This was what you might call the
distortion factor.

381
00:20:17,650 --> 00:20:21,220
That distortion factor, if the outcome is
rare, is going to be close to one.

382
00:20:21,220 --> 00:20:23,280
However, if the outcome is common, that
can,

383
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:25,360
distortion factor can be much different
than one.

384
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:26,390
That's the main point.

385
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:32,330
And people drawing, you know, graphs to
